resource.name: ​Train 100% of Employees in OSHA Requirements​
resource.description:
The initiative is on target with 73% of personnel trained. We anticipate to have at least an additional 20% of personnel trained in FY20 over FY19's total. This is a five year initiative that began in 2017. The goal is to have 20% of the County field workforce trained every year. The total number of employees that needs to be trained is an ever fluctuating figure due to turnover and new hires. The required percentages for years one through three have been achieved. Training for year four (FY20) and year five (FY21) is on track.

Beginning in year six, all supervisors, managers, and crew chiefs that oversee the field personnel will be required to take an 8 Hr. refresher course every five years.

resource.description: Redevelopment code focused on the relationships among buildings, sidewalks and streets, as well as promoting walkability. resource.name: Implement CIP Project Portfolio Management
resource.description:
CIP Project Portfolio Management is a collection of projects and programs, grouped to facilitate effective management of that work to meet strategic goals of the County through the Capital Improvement Plan process. The intent of this initiative is to adopt a portfolio approach to prioritizing capital projects and improve process for managing projects to enhance output, reporting, and decision support. Initiative deliverables include project prioritization criteria, portfolio development and project mapping processes, a CIP Project Management Handbook, an administrative directive, staff training, and centralized reports.
By establishing various working groups for this initiative, County staff have defined criteria to prioritize capital projects, developed a handbook and training for project managers, offered training to current county project managers, and developed a reporting tool to monitor capital projects.

Health in All Policies (HiAP) is a collaborative approach to improving the health of all people by incorporating health considerations into decision-making across sectors and policy areas.

 To improve health and equity, community partners came together to form the HiAP Pinellas County Collaborative. Partners include: Pinellas County Government, the City of Pinellas Park, the City of St. Petersburg, the Florida Department of Health in Pinellas County, Forward Pinellas, and the Foundation for a Healthy St. Petersburg. resource.name: Develop New County Website
resource.description:
The new County website project consists of the review, restructuring and  conversion of thousands of pages of content into a new content management system. It will:

1.Create a mobile-friendly site.

2.Create consistent user experience across the site.

3.Enable website visitors to find the information they need without having to understand the County's structure.

4.Provide access to information that resides on other county websites such as the Property Appraiser, Clerk, and Sheriff's sites through a multisite search.

5.Distribute content creation while centralizing final content review and site structure decisions.

6.Make the site compliant with the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA).

7.Update the design to make it better reflect Pinellas County as a progressive, forward-thinking local government.

resource.name: Develop Sustainability and Resiliency Education Resources
Develop Sustainability and Resiliency Action Plan (SRAP)
resource.description: The SRAP is a multi-year project to set the foundation and platform for sustainability and resiliency initiatives, planning, programs, policies, and solutions. This process will take an evidence-based, comprehensive approach to develop achievable strategic goals and objectives, measurable short to long-term actions, process integration, and decision-support tools. It will promote organizational and community-based sustainability and resiliency activities and programming in alignment with the County's Strategic Plan, structure, operations, and services. The SRAP will also prioritize the economic and social case for environmental sustainability, community resiliency, hazard mitigation, and climate change adaptation, including cost savings, economic opportunity, and self-sufficient programs.

resource.name: Develop the Mobile Home Park Improvement Strategy
resource.description: The Manufactured Housing Strategy identifies guiding principles and a prioritized list of actions to further the Pinellas County Comprehensive Plan (PCCP) and Affordable Housing Strategy. Recognizing the importance of manufactured housing as an option for many households, the County desires policies and programs to: encourage the preservation of existing manufactured home parks, the development of new manufactured home parks including increasing opportunities for resident-owned parks; and reduce or eliminate health and safety issues, and mitigate displacement and loss of housing. Strategies discussed ultimately must balance the needs of manufactured home owners/tenants, with the interests of park owners, and the feasibility of administration.
